# 3. Scale Up

## Infrastructure

```text
User
  |
  | HTTPS
  v
www.foobar.com
  |
  v
+---------------------+     +---------------------+
| Load Balancer 1     |<--->| Load Balancer 2     |
| HAProxy             |     | HAProxy             |
+----------+----------+     +----------+----------+
           |
           v
+---------------------+
| Web Server          |
| Nginx               |
+----------+----------+
           |
           v
+---------------------+
| Application Server  |
| App Code Base       |
+----------+----------+
           |
           v
+---------------------+
| Database Server     |
| MySQL               |
+---------------------+
```

## Explanation

A user wants to access `www.foobar.com`.

The browser sends an HTTPS request to the website.
The request reaches the HAProxy load balancer cluster.

The load balancers distribute traffic to the web server.
The web server, application server, and database are now separated into different servers.

This makes the infrastructure easier to scale, maintain, and monitor.

## Additional elements

### New server

We add one new server to separate infrastructure components.

Instead of running the web server, application server, and database on the same machine, each component can now have its own dedicated server.

This improves performance because each server has its own CPU, RAM, disk, and network resources.

### Second load balancer

We add a second HAProxy load balancer and configure it as a cluster with the first one.

This removes the load balancer as a Single Point of Failure.

If one load balancer fails, the other one can continue receiving traffic.

### Load balancer cluster

The two HAProxy load balancers work together as a cluster.

Usually, they share a virtual IP address.

One load balancer receives traffic, and if it fails, the second load balancer takes over.

This improves availability.

### Web server on its own server

The web server, usually Nginx, is placed on its own server.

Its role is to handle HTTP/HTTPS requests, serve static files, and forward dynamic requests to the application server.

Separating it makes it easier to scale web traffic independently.

### Application server on its own server

The application server is placed on its own server.

Its role is to execute the application code and process business logic.

Separating it improves performance and makes deployments easier.

### Database on its own server

The database, MySQL, is placed on its own server.

Its role is to store and manage application data.

Separating the database improves performance, security, and reliability because the database no longer competes with Nginx or the application server for resources.

## Application server vs Web server

### Web server

A web server handles HTTP/HTTPS requests from clients.

It can serve static files such as:

* HTML
* CSS
* JavaScript
* images

It can also forward dynamic requests to the application server.

Example:

```text
Nginx
```

### Application server

An application server runs the application code.

It handles the business logic of the website.

For example, it can:

* authenticate users
* process forms
* create orders
* interact with the database
* generate dynamic pages or API responses

Example:

```text
Node.js, Flask, Django, Ruby on Rails, PHP-FPM
```

## Why this infrastructure is better

This infrastructure is better because each component has a dedicated role.

Advantages:

* better performance
* easier scaling
* better fault isolation
* easier maintenance
* improved availability with two load balancers

If the website needs more capacity, we can add more web servers, more application servers, or improve the database layer separately.
